As you know, one of the biggest renju events every year is the Japanese meijin tournament,
where 10 strong Japanese masters fight for the win,
to have the chance to challenge the meijin
Mr LLIO is busy now,ha ha
our great GrandMaster Norihiko Kawamura won it
we are so happy and proud!
i will challenge him next year ...
It was tough games for me!
with half point less than Mr Kawamura
so, the game between Kawamura and Hasegawa was extremely important
It seems, he has given up his favorite opening - d11.
but, maybe because he feared Kawamura's strong d11 skill
Mr Kawamura has studied d11 a lot
Recently Hasegawa loves D3 instead of D11.
since d3 is considered better for white,
so most people never change color in d3
so we wil now go through the whole game,
to find the ideas, mistakes, etc
Since here are many newcomers, and beginners,
i will try to be slow, and explain more detailed
and show the wins to the very end
so you all will understand what is happening
The first 8 moves are not very surprising.
It is a very common beginning of d3
I need more detailed as a beginner
i7, h10 are two most common choices for white
then we can get similar position
however, here the white moves are forced
but in case of the upper 5th move,
white has the second choice as well, as we just talked
Mr Kawamura had probably prepared the lower 10th move
it leads to the traditional variant, which is often played in email tournaments,
but not so much used in real games
in live tournaments, people want to be more creative,
so they avoid traditional variants in live tournaments
but in offline games, the element of surprise is small,
so the traditional variants are often more effective
Actually, i dont know why Mr Hasegawa chose the traditional style for live game
as it is known, there is no good outcome for black in this variant after 16th move
samilar begining moves as the game between hasegawa and yamaguchi in 41st Meijin tournament
Perhaps, he hoped to confuse his opponent by an untraditional 17th move.
this situation here is a mix from two common patterns
but th following behavior of both players is by the stye of 14-k10
then this is a common style
it is very interesting to see the two styles mixed here.
but this seems stronger for white
is this variant now better or worse for black?
what do you think? and why?
Think this position is better because of the 15 move.
better for white, black was surrounded and without L9 stone in right side
i would play black j11 now
seems stonger in upper side,but if not win..
better for black,black can move h6 or g6 or j11,every point seems good
w stronger,but seems black also can active

up no good enough for win
White has a good position. But Black has more attacking posibilites in this variant. Although if white play strong white will win
compared to 14k10 i think now black is better
seems only me think black better
but i cann't answer the reason
y, black has tempo to stretch from 15-9 line
black has no connection to k8 now
but same time, white doesnt have so strong upper side
here stone 16 is a defense against 11
but in another variant, the line k7_i5 is open
i think this is very complicated situation
do you remember the concept of defense,
"if we have more than 1 choice, then we choose the defense which is most useful for outselves later"
even black i stronger below now than before,
then its ok to allow black stronger lower side
then white can enjoy bigger power later
please remember, the strongest defense is not always the best defense
sounds complicate for me as it is first time when i hear it
in order to promote our own stones
takes lots of courage and calculation
you must be sure, that the k7_i5 support, and the L7 support are not giving black win!
if it does, then this plan fails.
but it can be risky and difficult to asses
for medium level players and beginners,
if you want to use the pattern of whites at e8 and g12
but same time, the chance that black can later make easy draw is big
then you need to risk more
and choose the style as Kawamura did
what would you do here if you were white now?
first point that comes to mind isE9
At that time, Hasegawa lost a half game so far, so he tried to win, he said.
But white need to remember that black has tempo at the moment
you can attack when you see the win
you can attack if you want to fill up the board
but we never attack for win, if there is no win!
attack for defense applies for same rule,
we use the three for defense, if we have no other choice
otherwise, we just waste our power for no reason
meaning, if we have a suitable direct defense, and also the chance to defend by attacking,
and don't waste your attack power
because if you attack for defense,
the game may end with draw
because after black power is over,
the white power is over too
And psychologically, its also good to defend directly,
giving opponent the pressure of decision
but white want attack,and want black defend
jiang's F11 looks good. If white can control 17_21 white is secure.
white wants attack, but the position is not mature,
and immature attack will lead to the waste of all power

F11 or E12,if i move will chioce one
